Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
route_fix_ir(25.10)                                        route_fix_ir(25.10)

Name
       route_fix_ir  -  Fixes  IR  Drop  (voltage  drop)  violations  with the
       NanoRoute engine

Syntax
       route_fix_ir

       [-help]

       [-concurrent_pg_and_signal {0 1}]

       -ground_net <string>

       [-hotspot_boxes {{<lx1 ly1 ux1 uy1>} {<lx2 ly2 ux2 uy2>}...}]

       [-irdrop_threshold <float>]

       -power_net <string>

       [-rail_path <string>]

       -top_layer <string>

       Fixes IR Drop (voltage drop) violations with the NanoRoute  engine.  It
       creates  additional  PG connection paths from top layer PG stripes down
       to low layer PG rail shapes based on rail analysis results. This method
       also makes it possible to concurrently route signal nets  and  IR  drop
       fixing PG nets. It has congestion driven and timing aware capabilities.

       You can use the route_fix_ir command after postroute.

Parameters
       -concurrent_pg_and_signal {0 1}
              When  set  to 1, the NanoRoute router routes the signal nets and
              pg nets for  IR  drop  fixing  together.  When  set  to  0,  the
              NanoRoute router routes the PG net wires only and does not touch
              the signal nets.

              Default: 0

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -ground_net <string>
              Specifies the ground net name for IR drop fixing.

              Data_type: string, required

       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each route_fix_ir parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command

              man route_fix_ir.

       -hotspot_boxes {{<lx1 ly1 ux1 uy1>} {<lx2 ly2 ux2 uy2>}...}
              Specifies coordinates of the hotspot boxes.

              Note: When this option is specified, the  -rail_path  option  is
              ignored.

              Data_type: box_list, optional

       -irdrop_threshold <float>
              Specifies the minimum allowed voltage IR drop for the domain be-
              ing analyzed.

              Note: This option works with the -rail_path option.

              Data_type: float, optional

       -power_net <string>
              Specifies the power net name for IR drop fixing.

              Data_type: string, required

       -rail_path <string>
              Specifies  the  path of the rail analysis results. The NanoRoute
              router then calls the debug  IR  drop  functionality  to  create
              hotspot files.

              Note:  If the rail analysis path directory is not specified, the
              NanoRoute router automatically calls the  power  analysis,  rail
              analysis,  and  debug  IR drop functionalities to create hotspot
              files.

              Note: This option works with the -irdrop_threshold option.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -top_layer <string>
              Specifies the top stripe layer to connect the  PG  nets  for  IR
              drop fixing.

              Data_type: string, required

Examples
              * The  following  command  uses the rail analysis results for IR
                drop fixing.

                route_fix_ir  -rail_path rail_static/ALL_85C_avg_1  -top_layer
                M15 -irdrop_threshold 0.08 -power_net VDD -ground_net VSS

              * The following command specifies the hotspot boxes.

                route_fix_ir -hotspot_boxes {{box1} {box2} ...} -top_layer M15
                -power_net VDD -ground_net VSS

Related Information
              * analyze_rail

              * debug_irdrop

              * report_power

